<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-11-02T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-11-02T03:00:00-05:00" n="320" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d320">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/2429: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-11-02T16:00:00+08:00">November 2, 1931—4
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received November 2—6 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>859. Legation’s 830, October 29, 3 p.m.; and 858, November 2, 3 p.m.<note n="41" xml:id="d320fn41">Neither printed.</note></p>
                        <p>Wellington Koo, who returned here with the Marshal October 31st, requests
                            me to suggest that should the American Government contemplate action
                            similar to that taken by the British it would be extremely helpful to
                            the Commission, of which he has just been made chairman, if such
                            decision could be announced at the earliest date possible. He feels it
                            would lend moral support to the Commission when it was most needed.</p>
                        <p>Repeated to Shanghai.</p>
                        <closer>For the Minister:<lb/><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Engert</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>